  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is that when people from groups historically underrepresented in these fields feel the pressure of negative stereotypes about their abilities, it can impair their performance and confidence. As someone who grew up in a working-class family in Bologna without a strong academic focus, I've seen how this plays out in everyday life. My parents didn't emphasize STEM education much—they were more focused on practical skills like mechanics and carpentry. When I was in school, I often felt like my math and science grades were lower than my peers because I was worried about being labeled as 'not good at math.' This anxiety made it hard for me to focus during tests, even though I actually understood the material. I've noticed this in my own life too—when I work at the supermarket, I sometimes second-guess my ability to solve problems quickly, especially when it comes to things like inventory management or customer interactions. The stereotype that 'only smart people do STEM' can be a real barrier for people like me who don't have the same educational background as those who thrive in these fields. Addressing stereotype threat isn't just about changing policies—it's about creating environments where everyone feels safe to try and fail without judgment. Schools and workplaces should focus on building self-efficacy and celebrating diverse problem-solving approaches. For example, in my community, we could have workshops that show how everyday skills, like running or birdwatching, connect to scientific observation and data analysis. It's important to recognize that stereotypes aren't just about individual performance—they're about systemic issues that need to be addressed through empathy and practical support.",
